"""You can see the description of the task using the code specified in the title on leetcode.
This program has O(n) complexity by time and O(n) by space.

I really enjoyed the problem, but the negative numbers made it a bit more challenging. 
I still managed to come up with an equation for it, which was very satisfying. 

The key idea is that the total sum doesn't change, but the factors do. 
We can think of the shift as (each element of our sum has lost one multiplication operation, which corresponds to the sum of the array if we consider all the operations
, but the last element has shifted (the one that was first, with a factor of 0, has become last, with a factor of "array size")).

Fun fact: most solutions are based on "with each step, each element gains 1 to its multiplier," but mine is the opposite: 
"it loses 1 multiplier." 
The solution is valid, just a rotation in the other direction. 
It turns out I'm a divergent!
"""

class Solution:
    def maxRotateFunction(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        size = len(nums)
        window_sum = sum(nums)
        biggest_sum = prev_sum = sum(elem * idx for idx, elem in enumerate(nums))
        for i in range(1, size):
            prev_sum = prev_sum - window_sum + size * nums[i - 1]
            biggest_sum = max(biggest_sum, prev_sum)
        return biggest_sum
